In the Bash shell, the direct counterpart to Ctrl + W (which deletes backward) is Alt + D.

While Ctrl + W is a staple for most users, managing text effectively in the terminal usually involves a few different combinations depending on your terminal settings and whether you want to delete or just move.

The Breakdown
Action	Shortcut	Note
Delete Forward Word	Alt + D	Deletes from the cursor to the end of the current word.
Delete Backward Word	Ctrl + W	Deletes from the cursor to the start of the word.
Delete to End of Line	Ctrl + K	"Kills" everything from the cursor to the right.
Undo last deletion	Ctrl + _	Useful if you get a little too "delete-happy."
A Note on "Alt" vs "Meta"
In many terminal emulators (like those on macOS), the Alt key isn't mapped to the "Meta" key by default. If Alt + D just types a special character (like ∂) instead of deleting a word:

Open your Terminal Settings/Preferences.

Go to Profiles > Keyboard.

Check the box that says "Use Option as Meta key."

Alternative: The "Esc" Trick
If you don't want to mess with settings, you can press and release the Esc key and then press D. In Bash, Esc often acts as a prefix for Meta commands.

