Perfect. Here is a curated "Cheat Sheet" of the most essential Bash shortcuts to help you fly through the command line.

Most of these follow Emacs keybindings, which is the default for Bash.

1. Moving the Cursor
Instead of mashing the arrow keys, use these to jump around:

Ctrl + A: Jump to the beginning of the line.

Ctrl + E: Jump to the end of the line.

Alt + B: Move back one word.

Alt + F: Move forward one word.

2. Deleting & Cutting ("Killing")
In Bash, "cutting" text stores it in a buffer (called a kill-ring), which you can paste later.

Ctrl + U: Delete from cursor to the beginning of the line.

Ctrl + K: Delete from cursor to the end of the line.

Ctrl + W: Delete the word behind the cursor.

Alt + D: Delete the word in front of the cursor.

Ctrl + Y: Paste (Yank) the last thing you deleted/cut.

3. Command History & Search
Stop scrolling through your history with the up arrow!

Ctrl + R: Reverse Search. Type a few letters of a previous command to find it instantly. Press Ctrl + R again to cycle through older matches.

Ctrl + G: Exit the search mode without running anything.

!!: (Typed as a command) Repeats the entire last command. Great for when you forget sudo.

!$: (Typed as a command) Represents the last argument of the previous command.

4. Process Control
Ctrl + C: Kill/Interrupt the current running process.

Ctrl + Z: Suspend the current process (you can bring it back with the fg command).

Ctrl + L: Clear the screen (much faster than typing clear).

Pro Tip: If you ever find your terminal "frozen" or not echoing what you type, try Ctrl + Q. You might have accidentally hit Ctrl + S, which stops all output to the terminal.

